  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT219-kilavi">ciṟaippuṟam. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Hedge. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT219">

          <l>pacappeṉ mēṉi yatuvē nayappavar</l>
          <l>nāri ṉeñcat tāriṭai yatuvē</l>
          <l>ceṟivuñ cēṇikan taṉṟē yaṟivē</l>
          <l>yāṅkaṭ celka meḻukeṉa vīṅkē</l>
          <l>vallā kūṟi yirukku muḷḷilait</l>
          <l>taṭavunilait tāḻaic cērppaṟ</l>
          <l>kiṭamaṟ ṟōḻiyeṉ ṉīrō veṉiṉē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">

          <l>Pale is my body. Longing [is] in a place</l>
          <l>difficult [to reach], in his heart devoid of attachment.<note place="foot">Here the
            statement seems contradictory. Certainly <term xml:lang="ta">nayappu</term> is to be
            understood as subject, that is, as HER longing being on the way to HIS heart, and <term xml:lang="ta">ār-iṭai</term> in the sense of a place difficult to reach is well
            attested (cf. KT 131.3), but why difficult to reach if the longing is already there?
            Probably we have to understand an ellipsis: difficult to reach physically, if not
            mentally.</note>
          </l>
          <l>Even restraint stayed aside in the distance. Knowledge.<note place="foot">T.V.G. and
            Cām. construe one sentence from <term xml:lang="ta">aṟivu</term> up to <term xml:lang="ta">irukkum</term>.This would be a completely unmarked syntactical
            connection against every particle "rule", but it would make sense (see 3-5b).</note>
          </l>
          <l>To say here: “we shall go there, rise!”<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">eḻuk(a)
            eṉa</term> : again the special optative sandhi (cf. note on KT 141.2).</note>
          </l>
          <l>If I were to say<note place="foot">Traditionally the man is supposed to be the speaker
            of this question, but this does not make much sense. If SHE asks him, the point might be
            that she has been waiting for him to speak and now considers the possibility of forcing
            him into an open statement (a proposal of marriage?).</note> : “of what kind [are]
            you?”, friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent5">[that] indeed [would be] the opportunity for</l>
          <l rend="indent2">for the man from the coast of thorny-leafed, broad-based <term xml:lang="ta">Tāḻai</term> trees,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">who permanently <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta"> kūṟi irukkum</term>:
            can iru be auxiliary for a kind of continuous form?</note> talks without being able [to
            act].<note place="foot">In the very least from line 3 onwards construction and message
            of the poem are elusive and completely open to doubt. The <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi </term>
            conspicuously desists from any serious comment: "hedge".</note>
          </l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="3-5b" resp="#TVG">
            <l>Knowledge is speaking to me <note place="foot">
                <term xml:lang="ta">īṅkē </term> is by commentators sometimes explained to mean <term xml:lang="ta">eṉakku </term> (thus Cēṉ. on Tol. Col. 28).</note> , unable [to
              act]: “we'll go there, rise!”</l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
